 actor who has starred in films and appeared on television. <p>

He starred with Mercedes Hall (mother of Anthony Michael Hall) in Lanny Meyer and Arthur Morey's social protest disco musical, "St. Joan of the Microphone," which played New York City parks and festivals, including the Lincoln Center Outdoor Festival, in the summer of 1977. He created the role of the club heart-throb, Supersonic Phil Harmonic.</p>
<p>

His first feature film was in the horror movie <it>Dressed to Kill</it> (1980), but he is best known for his role in the 1981 horror movie <it><movie wordnetid="106613686" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../938/2274938.xml">
Friday the 13th Part 2</link></movie>
</it> as "Jeffrey". He also starred in the 1989 movie <it><movie wordnetid="106613686" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../841/1226841.xml">
Penn &amp; Teller Get Killed</link></movie>
</it>, and his most recent movie appearance was in the 1991 film <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../596/4887596.xml">
Guilty as Charged</link></it>.</p>
<p>

He made guest appearances on Tv shows such as <it><opera wordnetid="107026352" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../601/191601.xml">
As the World Turns</link></opera>
</it> and <it><series wordnetid="108457976" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../208/203208.xml">
Hill Street Blues</link></series>
</it>. Bill starred in the short lived TV series <it><link>
Comedy Zone</link></it> in 1984, and in the series <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../790/286790.xml">
Trauma Center</link></it>.</p>

